            Avicennia marina (Forssk.) Vierh. (Acanthaceae)
, which known as gray mangrove is a widely distributed mangrove species that thrives in high-salinity habitats (

; 

; 

). It is a main species of the mangrove forest ecosystem, which plays an essential role in supporting biodiversity, maintaining coastal stability, and protecting water quality (

). Iranian mangrove forests occur between the northern orbits 25°19′- 27°84’ (

). This area covers the north part of the Persian Gulf and 
Oman
Sea, and three coastal provinces in the south of 
Iran
(from southwest to southeast: 
Bushehr
, 
Hormuzgan
and Sistan & Balouchestan (

). It plays a significant role in supporting coastal ecosystem and holds unique potential for studying molecular mechanisms underlying ecological adaptation (

).

Mangrove trees are tolerant to high levels of heavy metals (

). Specially 

Avicennia
species

exhibit greater tolerance and have accumulative properties to numerous metals than other mangrove species (

; 

).


A. marina

like all other plants possess different cellular mechanisms to maintain the correct concentrations of essential metal ions in different cellular compartments and to minimize the damage from exposure to toxic concentration of essential and non-essential metals (

; 

). 
A
regulated network of metal transport, chelation, trafficking and sequestration activities maintain the metal homeostasis in the cell environment (

). Protein chelators including phytochelatins (PCs) and metallothioneins (MTs) are important chelating molecules that 
form stable
metal-complexes which are subsequently sequestered into vacuoles (

; 

; 

). MTs are low molecular weight, cysteine-rich, metal-binding proteins found in a wide variety of organisms including bacteria, fungi and all eukaryotic plant and animal species (

; 

). The ability of MTs for binding to metals through the thiol groups is their main function (

; 

; 

; 

). However they are also considered as scavenger of reactive oxygen species (ROS) (

; 

). Plant MTs are categorized in 
four types
based on the Cys distribution in amino acid sequences (

; 

). Whereas the MT 
types
1, 2 and 3 have two Cys-rich domain at N- and C- terminal that are separated by a linker of variable sizes. The MT 
type
4 is characterized with three Cys-rich domain (

; 

). With few exceptions, a typical 
type
1 MT contains six Cys residues in CXC motifs (where X denotes any amino acid other than Cys) at the N-terminal part. 
Type
2 MTs have eight Cys residues at their N-terminal arranged in CC, CXC, and CXXC motifs (

). 
Type
3 MTs are small proteins with four Cys residues in their N-terminal Cys-rich region (

). The distribution of Cys residues within the C-terminal part follows the consensus sequence CXCXXXCXCXXCXC that is highly conserved in all 
three types
. Until now the sequence of two members of MT families have been identified in 

A. marina
.

The protein AmMT2 with eight Cys residues at the N-terminal region has been classified into the 
type
2 MTs and AmMT3 with four Cys residues seems to be classified into typ 3 (

). In the present work the gene encoding AmMT2 has been cloned and heterologously expressed in 

E. coli

as fusion protein with glutathione-S-transferase (GST). The tolerance of transgenic cells in response to different metals and hydrogen peroxide was compared with the control strain. Because of high ability of strain for accumulation of Fe 
2+
, the ability of GST-AmMT2 for formation of complex with Fe 
+2
was investigated 
in vitro
and the effect of complex Fe 
2+
/GST-AmMT2 was studied on the catalase (CAT) activity.

The large scale production of protein was performed as described in part 2.3. The recombinant GST-AmMT2 was purified from the soluble fraction using nickel affinity chromatography and dialysis and the extent of purification was assessed by SDS-PAGE analysis (
Fig. 2B
).

Metallothioneins (MTs) are defined as a family of proteins with the characteristics of low molecular weight, high cysteine (Cys) residue content, and metal-binding ability (

; 

; 

). Plants have multiple members of MTs which are classified in 
four types
(

). Different MT 
types
seem to be differentially expressed in different plant organs. In Arabidopsis the genes encoding 
type
1 are predominantly expressed in root, 
type
2 in
aerial organs, 
type
3 in
ripening fruits as well as leaves and 
type
4 isoforms seem to be seed specific (

; 

; 

). The expression of genes encoding MTs are up-regulated in response to several abiotic stresses factors, including toxic concentration of heavy metals, salinity, drought, low temperature, abscisic acid and ethylene, suggesting different roles for MT protein family in plants. Recently several studies demonstrate the role of MTs as ROS scavengers, which may explain the enhanced expression of MT genes in response to above abiotic stress (

; 

; 

; 

). The protein AmMT2 from 

A. marina

is classified as 
type
2 plant MTs due to the presence of Cys-Cys and Cys-X-X-Cys motifs in the N-terminal domain (

).

The gene expression analysis of genes encoding type 2 MTs has been previously reported in some mangrove species. The significant increase in the transcript level of genes encoding AvMT2, BgMT2, KcMT2, and LlMT2 (
) in
Avicennia germinans ( Gonzalez-Mendoza et al., 2007 )
, Bruguiera gymnorrhiza (
) Kandelia candel (
), and Lupinus Luteus, respectively in the contaminated sites with Cu 2+ , Zn 2+ , Pb 2+ , Cd 2+ , Ni 2+ and Ag 1+ suggests that MT type 2 has a critical role in detoxification of heavy metals in the mangroves. Moreover the expression of genes encoding MTs has been also reported in response to oxidative stress. For instance the expression of BrMT (
), CgMT (
), GhMT (
) OsMT (
) or DpMT (
) decreased ROS production in transgenic plants or bacteria. The Arabidopsis T-DNA insertion mutant, mt2a, had higher H 2 O 2 levels than wild-type plants during cold stress (
). Here we describe a MT type 2 from
A. marina
with high ability for binding to Fe 2+ . The Ecoli cells expressing GST-AmMT2 were able to accumulate 30.7 mg Fe 2+ per g (dry weight cells) which is significantly higher than previous reports regarding to iron uptake by engineered
E. coli ( Grobe et al., 2006 )
. The production and purification of AmMT 2 in considerable amount enabled us to test the ability of binding of Fe 2+ to AmMT2. Both DTNB assay and UV absorption spectra demonstrate the formation of Fe 2+ /AmMT2 complex in vitro and confirm the binding ability of AmMT2 to Fe 2+ (
).

The transgenic
E. coli
showed also tolerance to hydrogen peroxide supporting the previous studies that found the heterologous expression of rice MT isoforms enhances the hydrogen peroxide tolerance in
E. coli cells
and
Saccharomyces cerevisae
(
;
). Hydrogen peroxide is a strong oxidising agent that dissociates to hydrogen ( H + ) and hydroxyl (OH − ) radicals. These oxidative agents readily attack proteins, lipids and nucleic acids. Several explanations for enhancement of tolerance of cells expressing MTs in response to H 2 O 2 are possible. First, MTs may act in zinc donation to apo-proteins, including zinc finger proteins (
). The presence of several zinc coordination sites in the zinc-finger proteins provides the opportunity for the transfer of zinc from MTs to these sites (
;
;
) Subsequently zinc finger transcription factors which are activated by zinc, regulate the expression of antioxidant genes resulted in enhancement of concentration of antioxidant enzymes in the cells (
). Secondly, the antioxidant enzymes such as CAT and superoxide dismutase (SOD) are metalloenzymes which require metal ions for activation (
;
;
;
). Therefore it is possible that MTs directly act as donator of ion metals to the metal binding site of these enzymes. In the present work we found that the activity of CAT in the transgenic strain expressing AmMT2 was significantly higher compared to control strain in response to H 2 O 2 . This may explain the higher tolerance of transgenic strain (R-AmMT2) in response to H 2 O 2 because the CAT is the key antioxidant enzyme in bacteria involved in elimination of H 2 O 2 . The enzyme CAT is an ubiquitous tetramer hemecontaining enzyme that catalyzes the dismutation of two molecules of H 2 O 2 into water and oxygen. Therefore the presence of Fe 2+ is required for the CAT activity. Here it has been shown that the Fe 2+ /AmMT2 complex enhances the activity of CAT in
E. coli
cell extract in vitro while the treatment with Apo/GST-AmMT2 did not affect on CAT activity. These results show that AmMT acts as activator for CAT by supplementation of Fe 2+ and by this way enhances the tolerance of cells

Overnight cultures of different strains were inoculated into 50 mL of LB medium with desired antibiotics and grown at 37 ° C under agitation. Protein expression was induced at an A 600 of 0.6 by addition of 0.1 mM IPTG . After 20 min, culture flasks were supplemented with 2 mM H 2 O 2. The cells from whole volume were harvested 4 h after addition of IPTG . For extraction of soluble proteins first the cells were resuspended in 40 ml buffer A (50 mM Tris-HCl, 50 mM Glucose, pH 7.8). Then the cells were harvested by centrifugation at 4 ° C for 20 min. The harvested cells were again resuspended in 3 ml buffer A containing 1 mg /ml lysozyme. The cell suspensions were kept at room temperature for 15 min. Then 3 ml of buffer B (50 mM Tris-HCl, 50 mM KCl, 1% Triton X-100) was added and the cell suspensions were shaken for 2 h at 37 ° C . Then the cell suspension was centrifuged (25 min, 4 ° C , 10000g ) to remove cell debris. The supernatant containing soluble protein was transferred to clean tubes and kept in – 20 ° C until use. The concentration of proteins was determined by the Bradford assay with bovine serum albumin as standard (
). The CAT activity was determined spectrophotometrically following H 2 O 2 consumption at 240 nM (
). A 500 μl reaction mixture containing 100 μg/ml extracted protein, 10 mM Tris-HCl, pH 7.4 was started with the addition of 20 μM H 2 O 2 . The reaction was monitored at 240 nm for 1 min and the rate of H 2 O 2 consumption was calculated (using the extinction coeffiecient of 36 M −1 Cm −1 ). One unit of CAT activity is defined as the degradation of 1 μmol H 2 O 2 /min. The CAT activity was compared between control and R-AmMT2 strains in the medium containing H 2 O 2 in
the presence or absence of IPTG . The data represent the mean ± SD obtained from two independent experiments with two replicates. The means were compared with least significant difference test (LSD, P 0.01) test.
